# Cursor AI & Project Best Practices

## General
- Prefer small, focused edits over large refactors. One concern per change.
- Use existing patterns and file structure; don’t invent new ones without reason.
- Run tests and lint after changes; fix any new failures before finishing.
- Never commit secrets, API keys, or `.env` (use `.env.example` for templates).

## Backend (NestJS)
- Keep controllers thin; put logic in services. Use DTOs with class-validator for input.
- Use the global ValidationPipe (whitelist, forbidNonWhitelisted, transform) as configured.
- Write unit tests for services; use Nest testing utilities and mocks for dependencies.
- Prefer dependency injection and Nest modules over global state or singletons.

## Frontend (React + Vite)
- Use functional components and hooks. Extract reusable logic into custom hooks.
- Prefer TypeScript types/interfaces for props and API responses.
- Call backend APIs via relative URLs or env-based base URL; handle loading and errors in UI.
- Keep components under ~200 lines; split or extract subcomponents when larger.

## Conventions (when applicable)
- Branch: `<ticket>_<Publisher>_<version>_<method>_<endpoint>_<defect_or_feature>`
- Commit: `<ticket> <Publisher> <version> <method> <endpoint> <short description>`
